(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number 3 :title "Chapter 3 — Tail recursion" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/03-tail-recursion.md" :size 9550 :sha256 "11cfbccd85cb5c01" :content "---\nslug: book-reference-ch-03\nbook: reference\nchapter: 3\ntitle: Tail recursion\npart: appendix\nof: reference-manual\napp: none\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Lane AJ)\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-10\npalette:\n  background: canvas-cream\n  top-band: magic\n  center: canvas-mint\n  ink: warm-plum\n  pink: sakura-pink (Sakura only)\nprev: 02-sorting-viz\nnext: 04-macros\n---\n\n# Chapter 3 — Tail recursion\n\nTwo versions of every function that recurses. The one you write first is the natural one — the one that mirrors the mathematical definition. The one you write second is the fast one — the one where the recursive call is the last thing the function does. This chapter is about that second one.\n\nTail recursion is a language feature more than an algorithm. Sakura Scheme, like every Scheme, guarantees that a recursive call in *tail position* does not grow the call stack. That means you can express iteration as recursion without paying for it — and in a language without a `for` loop, that guarantee is the whole reason recursion is practical for large inputs.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> When I write a function that recurses, I write the natural version first and check it works. Then, if I'm going to actually run it on real data, I rewrite it in tail form. The rewrite is almost always the same shape — an accumulator carried along the recursion, and the \"result\" being that accumulator at the base case.\n\n## Naive length — grows the stack\n\nStart with the natural version of `length`. It says exactly what length means: zero for empty, one plus the length of the rest otherwise.\n\n```scheme\n(define (naive-length lst)\n  (cond\n    ((null? lst) 0)\n    (else (+ 1 (naive-length (cdr lst))))))\n\n(display (naive-length '(a b c d e))) (newline)\n(display (naive-length '())) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n5\n0\n```\n\nFine for five elements. Not fine for five million, because every recursive call needs its own stack frame — the `+ 1` at the end needs the result of the inner call before it can finish, so the outer frame has to stick around.\n\n## Tail-recursive length — accumulator\n\nRewrite: carry the running count along as an accumulator. The recursive call is now the last thing that happens — nothing waiting for its return value.\n\n```scheme\n(define (length-loop lst acc)\n  (cond\n    ((null? lst) acc)\n    (else (length-loop (cdr lst) (+ acc 1)))))\n\n(define (length* lst)\n  (length-loop lst 0))\n\n(display (length* '(a b c d e))) (newline)\n(display (length* '(a b c d e f g h i j))) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n5\n10\n\n```\n\nThe `length-loop` function is a loop — the recursive call is the last expression in the `else` branch. Sakura Scheme's tail-call handling means this uses constant stack no matter how long the input list is.\n\n## Sum, both ways\n\nSame pattern, applied to `sum`.\n\n```scheme\n(define (naive-sum lst)\n  (cond ((null? lst) 0)\n        (else (+ (car lst) (naive-sum (cdr lst))))))\n\n(define (sum-loop lst acc)\n  (cond ((null? lst) acc)\n        (else (sum-loop (cdr lst) (+ acc (car lst))))))\n\n(define (sum* lst) (sum-loop lst 0))\n\n(display (naive-sum '(1 2 3 4 5))) (newline)\n(display (sum* '(1 2 3 4 5))) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n15\n15\n```\n\nSame answer. The `sum*` version is a loop and runs in constant stack.\n\n## Fibonacci — the classic bad recursion\n\nThe naive recursive Fibonacci is textbook exponential — every call spawns two more.\n\n```scheme\n(define (naive-fib n)\n  (cond ((< n 2) n)\n        (else (+ (naive-fib (- n 1))\n                 (naive-fib (- n 2))))))\n\n(display (naive-fib 10)) (newline)\n(display (naive-fib 20)) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n55\n6765\n```\n\n`(naive-fib 20)` performs about 21,000 function calls to compute a single number. `(naive-fib 40)` performs about 300 million. Do not run `(naive-fib 40)` in a REPL you care about.\n\n## Fibonacci with an accumulator\n\nTwo accumulators — the previous two values — and a countdown.\n\n```scheme\n(define (fib-loop n a b)\n  (cond ((= n 0) a)\n        (else (fib-loop (- n 1) b (+ a b)))))\n\n(define (fib* n) (fib-loop n 0 1))\n\n(display (fib* 10)) (newline)\n(display (fib* 20)) (newline)\n(display (fib* 40)) (newline)\n(display (fib* 100)) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n55\n6765\n102334155\n354224848179261915075\n```\n\n`(fib* 100)` runs in the time it takes to display the answer. That is the difference tail recursion makes: exponential to linear, and the linear version fits in constant stack too.\n\n## Named `let` — the Scheme sugar\n\nScheme has a shorthand for tail-recursive helpers: named `let`. The name of the inner `let` is the recursion point.\n\n```scheme\n(define (fib** n)\n  (let loop ((k n) (a 0) (b 1))\n    (cond ((= k 0) a)\n          (else (loop (- k 1) b (+ a b))))))\n\n(display (fib** 10)) (newline)\n(display (fib** 20)) (newline)\n(display (fib** 40)) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n55\n6765\n102334155\n```\n\n`loop` is not a keyword — it is the name given to the anonymous inner function that the named `let` creates. `(loop (- k 1) b (+ a b))` is a tail call to that function.\n\n## Tree-sum — recursion that isn't always tail\n\nNot everything can be made tail-recursive without an explicit stack. Tree traversal is the classic case: at each node, you recurse into two children, and the result is a function of both.\n\n```scheme\n(define (make-node value left right) (list 'node value left right))\n(define (node-value n) (list-ref n 1))\n(define (node-left n)  (list-ref n 2))\n(define (node-right n) (list-ref n 3))\n(define (leaf? n) (and (null? (node-left n)) (null? (node-right n))))\n\n(define t\n  (make-node 1\n    (make-node 2 (make-node 4 '() '()) (make-node 5 '() '()))\n    (make-node 3 (make-node 6 '() '()) (make-node 7 '() '()))))\n\n(define (tree-sum n)\n  (cond ((null? n) 0)\n        (else (+ (node-value n)\n                 (tree-sum (node-left n))\n                 (tree-sum (node-right n))))))\n\n(display (tree-sum t)) (newline)  ;; 1+2+3+4+5+6+7 = 28\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n28\n```\n\n`tree-sum` is not tail-recursive — the outer `+` needs both children's sums before it can add. That's fine for balanced trees (stack depth stays log(n)); it's not fine for deep unbalanced trees where you can blow the stack.\n\n## Tree-sum with an explicit stack\n\nTo make tree traversal iterative, you keep the \"still-to-visit\" nodes in your own list — an explicit stack — instead of relying on Scheme's call stack.\n\n```scheme\n(define (make-node v l r) (list 'node v l r))\n(define (node-value n) (list-ref n 1))\n(define (node-left n)  (list-ref n 2))\n(define (node-right n) (list-ref n 3))\n\n(define t\n  (make-node 1\n    (make-node 2 (make-node 4 '() '()) (make-node 5 '() '()))\n    (make-node 3 (make-node 6 '() '()) (make-node 7 '() '()))))\n\n(define (tree-sum-iter root)\n  (let loop ((stack (list root)) (acc 0))\n    (cond\n      ((null? stack) acc)\n      ((null? (car stack)) (loop (cdr stack) acc))\n      (else\n       (let ((n (car stack)))\n         (loop (cons (node-left n) (cons (node-right n) (cdr stack)))\n               (+ acc (node-value n))))))))\n\n(display (tree-sum-iter t)) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n28\n```\n\nSame answer, but now the recursion is one `loop` call — a tail call — and the \"which nodes remain\" state is in the `stack` argument, not in Scheme's call stack. This version handles arbitrarily deep trees.\n\n## Range-based counting\n\nA sanity check: count from 1 to 1,000,000 using a tail-recursive loop. This would blow a naive recursion's stack immediately.\n\n```scheme\n(define (count-to n)\n  (let loop ((k 1) (acc 0))\n    (cond ((> k n) acc)\n          (else (loop (+ k 1) (+ acc k))))))\n\n(display (count-to 100)) (newline)\n(display (count-to 10000)) (newline)\n;; try a big one in your own REPL — this book's build keeps it small.\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n5050\n50005000\n```\n\nTen thousand iterations, one tail call each time, constant stack. Try `(count-to 1000000)` in your own REPL — the wall time is measurable but the stack usage isn't.\n\n## Under the hood — what tail-call means for the runtime\n\n> **Under the hood**\n>\n> A tail call is a call in a position where nothing needs to happen after the callee returns. When Sakura Scheme sees a tail call, it replaces the current stack frame with the callee's frame instead of pushing a new one on top. The mechanical result is that `(loop ...)` in tail position uses one stack frame no matter how many times it's called. The consequence is that recursion is the loop construct in Scheme — you don't need `while` or `for`, because `let` + tail-call gives you the same guarantee at zero cost.\n\n## What you know now\n\n- Every recursive function has a natural version and a tail-recursive version.\n- Tail recursion means the recursive call is the last thing the function does.\n- Named `let` is Scheme's sugar for a tail-recursive helper.\n- Fibonacci naive is exponential; Fibonacci with an accumulator is linear.\n- Tree recursion isn't always naturally tail-recursive — for deep trees, use an explicit stack.\n- The runtime guarantees constant stack for tail calls; that's what makes recursion practical for real inputs.\n\n## Try before you turn the page\n\nAuthor a tail-recursive factorial that returns the product of `1..n`.\n\n```scheme\n(define (fact n)\n  (let loop ((k n) (acc 1))\n    (cond ((= k 0) acc)\n          (else (loop (- k 1) (* acc k))))))\n\n(display (fact 5))   (newline)  ;; 120\n(display (fact 10))  (newline)  ;; 3628800\n(display (fact 20))  (newline)  ;; 2432902008176640000\n```\n\nIf `(fact 20)` produces `2432902008176640000` without complaint, your factorial is tail-recursive and Sakura Scheme's numeric tower is doing its job. On to Chapter 4.\n\n---\n\n*Chapter 4 — Macros.*\n")
